types.section:
{{fr-adj}}

# [[unknown]], [[obscure]], [[unfamiliar]], [[strange]]
#: {{ux|fr|Le hurling est un sport '''inconnu''' en dehors de l{{'}}Irlande.|The sport of hurling is unknown outside Ireland.}}

{{fr-noun|m|f=+}}

# an [[unknown]] person, place, or thing; a [[stranger]]
#: {{ux|fr|L{{'}}'''inconnu''' au bar m{{'}}a souri.|The stranger at the bar smiled at me.}}
# {{lb|fr|no plural}} the things one does not know, in contrast to what one does
#* {{quote-book|fr|year=1844|author=Honoré de Balzac|title=Modeste Mignon|chapter=IX|page=181|text=Ernest demeura fasciné par le gouffre de l’'''inconnu'''. L’'''inconnu''', c’est l’infini obscur, et rien n’est plus attachant.|t=Ernest remained fascinated by the abyss of the '''unknown'''. The '''unknown''' is obscure infinity, & nothing is more enthralling.}}

====Usage notes====
* The word '''{{m|fr||inconnu}}''' refers to someone or something not previously encountered and totally unknown; a related term, {{m|fr|méconnu}}, refers to something that has been encountered or someone acquainted, but is not entirely familiar.<ref>{{cite-web |url=https://blog.alorthographe.com/2016/09/20/inconnu-et-meconnu/ |title=Inconnu et méconnu {{!}} Blog alorthographe |accessdate=23 June 2022 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210928140010/http://blog.alorthographe.com/2016/09/20/inconnu-et-meconnu/ |archivedate=28 September 2021 }}</ref><ref>[https://hinative.com/en-US/questions/14888325 What is the difference between "inconnu" and "méconnu" ? "inconnu" vs "méconnu" ? | HiNative]</ref>

